It seems that the problem is caused by the fact that the view holding the keyboard and its keys is not being repositioned properly when the keyboard is downsized. 

One solution is to update the position of the view in addition to its height. You can do this by calling `setY()` on the view after calling `requestLayout()`. The y-value should be the difference in height between the original and new keyboard heights.

For example:

```java
@Override
public void onStartInputView(final EditorInfo editorInfo, final boolean isRestarting)
{
  super.onStartInputView(editorInfo, isRestarting);

  for (final Keyboard keyboard : keyboardSet)
  {
    keyboard.adjustKeyboardHeight();
  }
  inputContainer.updateHeight();

  // Calculate difference in height
  int originalHeight = inputContainer.getHeight();
  int newHeight = calculateNewKeyboardHeight(); // replace with your calculation
  int heightDiff = originalHeight - newHeight;

  // Update height and position of inputContainer
  inputContainer.requestLayout();
  inputContainer.setY(inputContainer.getY() + heightDiff);
}
``` 

This should ensure that the keyboard view is properly repositioned when downsized.

Yes, you can trigger the automatic reposition programmatically by calling `View.animate()` method. You can create a smooth animation that resizes and repositions the keyboard view simultaneously.

Here's an example code snippet:

```java
// Determine the new height of the keyboard
int newHeight = calculateNewKeyboardHeight(); // replace with your calculation

// Determine the difference in height
int heightDiff = inputContainer.getHeight() - newHeight;

// Animate the height and position of the keyboard
inputContainer.animate()
    .translationY(heightDiff)
    .setDuration(250)
    .start();
```

In this example, we first calculate the new height of the keyboard as you were already doing. Then we calculate the difference in height. Finally, we animate the keyboard view to move by the difference in height using the `animate()` method of the `View` class. 

The `translationY()` method sets the difference in Y-position of the view relative to its original position. We use the `setDuration()` method to set the duration of the animation, and finally, call `start()` to start the animation.

This should result in a smooth animation that resizes and repositions the keyboard view simultaneously without requiring the user to touch the SeekBar again.

Yes, you can reposition the keyboard view automatically without calculating the height difference. One way to do this is to wait for the layout to be updated by the `requestLayout()` method before repositioning the view.

Here's an example code snippet:

```java
// Determine the new height of the keyboard
int newHeight = calculateNewKeyboardHeight(); // replace with your calculation

// Resize the keyboard
inputContainer.getLayoutParams().height = newHeight;
inputContainer.requestLayout();

// Reposition the keyboard after the layout is updated
inputContainer.post(new Runnable() {
    @Override
    public void run() {
        int screenHeight = getResources().getDisplayMetrics().heightPixels;
        int keyboardHeight = inputContainer.getHeight();
        int keyboardY = screenHeight - keyboardHeight;
        inputContainer.setY(keyboardY);
    }
});
```

In this example, we first calculate the new keyboard height as you were already doing. Then we resize the keyboard by updating its layout parameters and requesting a layout update using `requestLayout()`. 

After requesting the layout update, we wait for the layout to be updated by posting a new `Runnable` to the `View` using the `post()` method. In the `Runnable`, we calculate the new Y-position of the keyboard by subtracting its height from the screen height.

This should result in automatic repositioning of the keyboard view without requiring the user to touch the SeekBar again.

