To retrieve data from this structure, you can handle user input in the following way:

1. Let the user enter their phone number instead of a node name.
2. Modify the `retrieveData` function to search for the phone number in the "users" node and retrieve all the child nodes under it.

I have updated the relevant parts of the `Result.java` file for you, based on your database structure:

```java
public class Result extends AppCompatActivity {
    // ... other member variables ...
    private DatabaseReference mDatabaseRef;
    // ... onCreate function ...

    private void retrieveData(String phoneNumber) {
        DatabaseReference myRef = mDatabaseRef.child(phoneNumber); // Get reference for entered phone number

        myRef.addListenerForSingleValueEvent(new ValueEventListener() {
            @Override
            public void onDataChange(@NonNull DataSnapshot dataSnapshot) {

                mData.clear(); // Clear the previous data

                // Loop through all child nodes (unique identifiers)
                for (DataSnapshot idSnapshot : dataSnapshot.getChildren()) {
                    // Loop through each child node's content
                    for (DataSnapshot dataSnapshot : idSnapshot.getChildren()) {
                        String name = dataSnapshot.getKey();
                        String data = dataSnapshot.getValue().toString();
                        mData.add(new Pair<>(name, data)); // Add the key-value pair to the data list
                    }
                }

                mAdapter.notifyDataSetChanged(); // Notify the adapter about the data change
            }

            @Override
            public void onCancelled(@NonNull DatabaseError databaseError) {
                Log.w(TAG, "Failed to read value.", databaseError.toException());
            }
        });
    }
}
```

